Friends, I've figured out the perfect Valentine's Day gift - a black truffle! Heck, gift yourself one. Order yours at www. freshwild.com or call 800-222-5578. Order by 12:00 PT Wednesday, February 8 for Valentine's Day delivery. And, for 10% off your first order use the checkout code VDAY10! Risotto recipe below for your menu planning needs.

Black Truffle Risotto
8 to 10 cups chicken or vegetable stock 
4 tablespoons (1⁄2 stick/55 g) unsalted butter
2 tablespoons olive oil
Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
1⁄2 medium yellow onion finely chopped
2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
1 1/2  cups (285 g) Aborio rice
1⁄2 cup (120 ml) dry white wine
1⁄4 cup (25 g) freshly grated pecorino cheese, plus more for garnish 
2 tablespoons black truffle butter 
1 large black truffle for shaving 
Flaky salt, for finishing

In a large Dutch oven or stockpot, bring the chicken stock to a simmer over medium heat.

In another large Dutch oven or deep-sided 12-inch (30.5 cm) skillet, melt 2 tablespoons of the butter and heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add
add the onion and cook, stirring frequently, until they soften, 4 to 5 minutes. Add the garlic and cook for 30 seconds more. Season well with kosher salt.
Add the rice to the pan, stir to coat with the buttery onions, and let the rice toast for 2 to 3 minutes. Stir in the wine and cook until it
evaporates, 2 minutes or so.

Begin adding the simmering stock to the rice, about 1⁄2 to 3⁄4 cup (120 to 180 ml) at a time, stirring constantly. Repeat with the remaining stock, cooking and stirring until the rice is creamy but still al dente, 30 minutes or so. Taste it along the way so you know where you’re at in terms of
consistency. You may not need to use all of the stock, but better to have more on hand than less in case you do. Turn off the heat and stir in the grated cheese and the truffle butter.  Plate in bowls and shave truffles on top of each portion and season with flaky salt more grated cheese if you like.

My lack of baking can be problematic when entertaining. ⁠
⁠
Things potentially get awkward at the end of a meal when your host offers you nothing except for more wine. (I always have plenty.)⁠
⁠
So, if a guest cheerfully asks, “What can I bring?” I will always answer honestly, “Please bring dessert.” Because, in fact, I do have friends that truly enjoy making and eating it. (Fine, I’ll have a small piece with whipped cream.)⁠
⁠
And, if you too do not bake or don't bake well, I suggest you feel no shame, give in, and do the same. That way, everyone’s a winner.⁠

Dinner Again! A collection of my recent weeknight dinners to satisfy every palate.

Summer is in full swing so I’m soaking in every moment, while eating fabulously every night. It doesn’t have to be hard. It can be quick and so, so delicious.
⁠
I don’t want to beat around the bush, so let’s get to it. What I’ve really been cooking day to day.⁠ 👇
⁠
🍷 Drinking: @thewaves.wine club. A very cool new way to learn, drink and get natural wines delivered! I sampled a few of the wines, all delightful.⁠
⁠
MONDAY: Roast Salmon with Tomato Butter, New Potatoes with so much Butter and Sautéed String Beans. Potatoes were boiled until fork tender and tossed with an obscene amount of salted butter - I buy @cows_creamery when I’m in #NovaScotia.⁠
⁠
TUESDAY: Dan and Helen arrived and I made them a version of this very good Sweet Corn and New Potato Chowder. I did add some lobster meat to everyone's bowls before ladling - there were no complaints.⁠
⁠
WEDNESDAY: Dan made Pasta alla Boscaiola, an testkichen_ recipe, it was outrageously good. So good I might even subscribe to ATK? No notes.⁠
⁠
THURSDAY: Marinated some pork chops from Nic Nat Farm @eatlocalcumberland (harissa! honey! garlic! line juice!) and grilled them quickly over a hot fire.⁠
⁠
FRIDAY: Oysters and Pizza Night! Need I say more? Gorgeous #Beausoleil #oysters from New Brunswick and a double batch of pizza dough, recipe from @pizzeriabianco in @foodandwine⁠ — it comes together quite fast.⁠
⁠
We snacked on classic gingersnaps purchased in the grocery aisle at @realatlanticss⁠ for dessert. A perfect evening. ⁠
⁠
Plan out your weeknight meals easily by viewing this week's edition of Dinner Again on the substack.⁠ More details on each dish in the link in bio and Stories.
⁠

As we (crazily) hit mid-August, I’m sharing some simple, summery things I’ve done these last few weeks, which made me feel like it was “proper summer.” I recommend you try some of them and you will too. 

I’d also love to hear what you’d add to the list!

1️⃣ Make yourself a vanilla ice cream cone, drizzle it with olive oil and a few pinches of flaky salt.
2️⃣ Make a big pot of clams at least a few times a few different ways.
3️⃣ Make someone else’s recipes from time to time - it helps when you’re in a rut. I made a life changing rice gratin (twice!) from Claire Thomson's (@5oclockapron) Home Cookery Year. 
4️⃣ Go for a cold swim every morning if you’re able or alternatively take a cold shower. It really shakes off whatever you need it to.
5️⃣ Drink your morning cup of coffee outside with a book. Leave your phone in your bedroom. 

More summer to-do’s in my Substack newsletter.

How to summer part II!

6️⃣ Pet as many dogs as you can. 
7️⃣ Cook in your swimsuit. It’s liberating. Read Sarah Copeland’s lovely newsletter @edibleliving and her piece How to Cook Like You Live In St.Tropez all about it. 
8️⃣ Top and tail string beans or shuck corn with a friend at a picnic table and sip rosé while doing it.
9️⃣ Hang your sheets outside to dry in the sun.
🔟 Clean out your fridge. Make an inventory list, pin it to the fridge door and cross out things as you use them. It’s wildly satisfying.

See previous vanilla ice cream post for 1-5.

We are empty nesters for the first time all summer and I’m trying to find my rhythm. The crickets have arrived along with their nightly, prayerful songs, which gestures late summer, but I’m not quite ready to let go just yet. In some ways, it feels like summer never really started. I’m not trying to be a pessimist, we were blessed with rich visits from dear friends and good meals, but with the finicky weather (the woman at the wine store said she was surprised we hadn’t all turned to mold, ha!), the construction zone that is currently our home and looming deadlines (hello, book #3), I suppose it's fair to say it hasn’t been footloose and fancy free. Or perhaps I’ll forever be searching for one that reminds me of childhood?

This version of eggplant Parm has been in my family for decades. I’ve truthfully never seen it prepared like this anywhere else. Unlike other traditional recipes I’ve come across, there are no breadcrumbs in this version, hence why I call it “𝙔𝙤𝙪’𝙡𝙡 𝙉𝙚𝙫𝙚𝙧 𝙐𝙨𝙚 𝘽𝙧𝙚𝙖𝙙𝙘𝙧𝙪𝙢𝙗𝙨 𝙛𝙤𝙧 𝙔𝙤𝙪𝙧 𝙋𝙖𝙧𝙢 𝘼𝙜𝙖𝙞𝙣!” 𝙀𝙜𝙜𝙥𝙡𝙖𝙣𝙩 𝙋𝙖𝙧𝙢 — make it a day in advance for easier slicing and melded flavors.

Lobster Salad… on a Bun or Not?

It isn’t summer without eating lobster at least once, or a number of times if you are so fortunate. 

And so, on the beloved ramshackle deck that looks onto the Peconic, attached to the house my dad rents in Hampton Bays, my lobster salad recipe came to be. 

It’s a simple lobster salad, but I like to treat myself and take the  extra step of making aioli for it.  See slide two for the swoopy aioli. 💛

I like my lobster salad on soft, tender lettuces with an assortment of items surrounding it, such as thick wedges of tomato, avocado, jammy eggs, and blanched green beans, with some more aioli on the side for dipping. 

Chad likes his served on a toasted buttered bun. However you like to eat it, please do so outside, overlooking the water.

Linked the recipe in my Stories today 🦞

I’m crazy for clams - specifically hard shelled ones from the quahog family, which include littlenecks, cherrystones, etc.. 

Soft shell clams (AKA piss clams or steamers - no, you can’t eat the shell) are a real thing in this part of Nova Scotia and they are just not for me.

More clam recipes anyone? I’ll link in Stories.

My wanderlust has peaked, and in my mind I’m in #Italy with friends in a big house by the sea. 

We likely have just gotten home from the beach and are rummaging through the kitchen to make a late lunch. 

I find some cucumbers and some local mozzarella and begin to assemble a salad so simple, it deserves the very best of ingredients. 

I place it on the table with some thickly cut pieces of toasted bread rubbed with garlic and perhaps a plate of sliced, still-warm-from-the-sun tomatoes, and figs too. 

We sit outside and drink fizzy wine and afternoon slips into evening and we laugh a lot.

Happy Saturday ☀️

My less-is-more list for cooking essentials to have in your kitchen. Let’s start with Pots and Pans. 

Lodge cast iron skillet: Frankly, I could get by with this 12-inch pan and my Dutch oven alone, but if you must, buy two. @lodgecastiron is the best, IMO. If they are taken care of, they will last a lifetime.

Large Dutch oven: My favorite kitchen item. I’m partial to @staub_usa

Colander/Stainer: You know, for draining pasta water and other items such as vegetables.

The weather is most certainly fall today, so I put a pot of stock on this morning. 

I find there is an element of self-care in the ritual. This also means soup tonight…! 

So here’s a recipe for… Some Broth, Some Fregola, Some Broccoli Rabe, and Crispy Prosciutto.

INGREDIENTS

2 tablespoons olive oil

3 ounces (85 g) prosciutto, roughly chopped or torn

into 1- to 11⁄2-inch (2.5 to 4 cm) pieces

1 medium yellow onion, finely chopped

1 medium stalk celery, thinly sliced

3 cloves garlic, finely chopped

1⁄2 teaspoon red pepper flakes

1 tablespoon tomato paste

Kosher salt

6 cups (1.4 L) chicken stock

1⁄2 cup (90 g) fregola or pearled couscous

1 bunch broccoli rabe, roughly chopped into 1-inch(2.5 cm) pieces

Topping suggestions: soft-boiled eggs, chili crisp, roughly chopped celery leaves, freshly grated pecorino or Parmesan cheese

METHOD

In a large Dutch oven or stockpot, heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add the prosciutto and cook, stirring occasionally, until it begins to crisp and brown in spots, 2 to 3 minutes. Remove from the pot and place on a paper towel–lined plate.

Add the onion and the celery to the pot and cook, stirring occasionally until they begin to soften, 4 to 5 minutes. Stir in the garlic, red pepper flakes, and tomato paste and cook for 1 to 2 minutes more. Season well with salt.

Pour in the chicken stock and when it comes to a boil add the fregola and turn down the heat to a simmer. About 5 minutes before the pasta is finished cooking, add the broccoli rabe to the broth and stir until it wilts and cooks down a bit. Taste and adjust seasoning with salt to taste. Ladle the broth into bowls, making sure you get some fregola and broccoli rabe in each one, and top each portion with some of the crisped-up prosciutto and any of the other toppings I’ve suggested or that you prefer.

A Pot of Beans 🫘 

I have made beans on a weekly basis for years (mostly on Sundays), so I can use them in meals throughout the week. They are dependable, comforting, and delicious. Not only do they have the ability to serve as a satisfying, delightful meal on their own, they also offer you the flexibility of using them to transform an already existing dish. There isn’t much a bean can’t do.

In this week’s newsletter I sent out my tried and true method for beans (soak + salt!), a very controversial topic.

There are many theories on the best way to cook a pot of beans. People can be very particular: to soak or not to soak, to salt the water and soak or not, to change the soaking water before boiling or not and so on and so forth. The truth is, it doesn’t really matter that much in the end as long as you end up with a pot of creamy beans in a rich and flavorful broth.

On again off again rainy October days call for chicken soup.

Here’s my method for chicken and rice soup with snap peas and lots of ginger…

In a large pot or Dutch oven heat the oil over medium heat. When it shimmers add the scallions, garlic, ginger, and chillies. Cook, stirring occasionally under they softened, but take on no real color, 4 to 6 minutes. Season with salt. 

Add in the chicken broth, chicken thighs and the rice and season with salt. Turn heat to medium-high and bring to a rapid simmer. Turn back to medium and bring back to a low simmer and cook for 20 to 30 minutes, until the chicken is cooked through and the rice is toothsome.

Using tongs, remove the chicken from the pot and transfer to a medium bowl or plate. Shred the chicken into pieces, then stir it back into the soup along with the snap peas and the soy sauce. Taste and adjust seasonings accordingly with salt. Ladle into bowls and top with your garnishes of choice.

It’s Monday. It’s Fall. It’s the perfect day for a 30 minute mushroom dinner 🍄 

My friend Devon Gilroy runs an incredible mushroom farm here in the Hudson Valley called @tivolimushrooms. 

When the pandemic hit, many of his restaurant accounts closed and he quickly pivoted, doing online orders of mushrooms for regular people like myself, and I was very eager to support. 

His mushrooms are the most beautiful I have ever seen and, for a good part of the spring, I happily ate mostly mushrooms, which is how this recipe came about. 

I roast them until they turn beautifully crisp and golden and plate them on top of a generous amount of sour cream; the opposition of textures and temperature just work. 

The dish is finished with a showering of your choice of herbs and my choice of lemon zest. I also like to drizzle the dish with chili or herb oil, depending on what’s in my fridge. Serve alongside anything.

As I continue my boycott of all hallows eve, I implore you to begin planning for the laziest of weekends ahead. 

Thus, queue my Wild Rice and Mushroom Soup with Tarragon recipe.

This is a very good soup and it can be tweaked easily to your liking. I chose to use tarragon because it was at the farm store this week looking particularly verdant. However, I know some people have strong feelings about tarragon, so feel free to swap in thyme or sage, or a combination of both. I also call for a leek. Should you not have a leek, use a yellow onion or a very large shallot. I did not have wine on hand nor dry vermouth, but if I did, I would have used a ½ cup to deglaze the pan before the broth goes in. Lastly, I added heavy cream just before serving.

It’s just a bit, but you can of course leave it out or add in a vegan substitute. I am not well-versed in this area, so I trust if you’re going with this option, you are. So I’ll leave that to you.

Salted. Chocolate. Buckwheat. Cookies…! @bybrianlevy cookie recipe is right my alley as they lean a bit savory. They also happen to be gluten free should you also be.

I’ll be sharing bits and bobs from the interview I did with Brian for my Substack, but in the meantime read it in the link in my Stories!

Photo by Kristin Teig, styling by Catrine Kelty
As told by @bybrianlevy in my Substack this week!

A very delicious and fast sausage sugo — your MVP this holiday season! 

You’re using sausage, which already has so much flavor, so the sauce doesn’t need to simmer that long to bring it all together and make it more than the sum of its parts. 

It works just as beautifully served over polenta as it does tossed with pasta or tucked in between sheets of lasagna. 

Your options are endless here. I’d also be just as happy eating with a big hunk of toasted sesame bread 🥖 

Linked the recipe in Stories! 📷 @taradonne.studio

It’s time to get festive, people. Doesn’t get much easier than jammy eggs with chilis and flaky salt, but I’m putting together NYE ideas for you, so send along your requests! Tinned fish? Cocktails? Braises? Let’s hear it.

Photo by @taradonne.studio for my cookbook.

Do not underestimate the power of a toast bar when hosting…! 

Fancy toast can feed a crowd, feels festive, and some premixing of ingredients means when all those cousins and uncles show up you can put them to work on assembling.

Photos for my book taken by @taradonne.studio

A perfect NYE menu a la @bybrianlevy — featuring meringue in the dessert course!

Cocktail: Boulevardier

Hors d’oeuvres: An old-fashioned brie en croute (cheese baked in puff pastry); bresaola (cured beef)

Appetizer: A shaved Brussels sprouts salad with almond, parmesan, currants; Hamachi crudo

Main: Peking duck

Dessert: Mont Blanc (Meringue, chestnut puree, whipped cream. I love chestnuts.) 

Late night: PIZZA

Plenty of champagne at each course, obviously.

Photo by @taradonne.studio

Truly thrilled to partner with the most wonderful @pasta_rummo and create a dish for my favorite, favorite Italian-American Christmas Eve tradition, Feast of the Seven Fishes. Pasta Rummo is a 177-year-old family-run brand rooted in tradition and is slow-crafted ("lenta lavorazione"), which allows for perfectly al dente pasta every time. This recipe has three fishes, so you're almost halfway there! See below and Buon Natale! 

Spicy Linguine with "Three Fishes"

INGREDIENTS
1 pound Rummo linguine 
1 dozen littleneck clams
1 pound mussels 
½ cup white wine 
3 tablespoons olive oil 
1 large shallot, finely chopped 
6 garlic cloves, finely chopped 
2 teaspoons Calabrian chili paste or 1 teaspoon dried chili flakes 
2 pints cherry or grape tomatoes 
¾ pound large shrimp 
2 tablespoons, finely chopped Italian parsley 

METHOD
Bring a large pot of well-salted water to a boil. Add pasta, and cook until it is al dente, according to package directions. Reserve 1 cup of the pasta cooking water, and drain.

Meanwhile, steam the shellfish. Heat a large Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the mussels and the clams and pour in the white wine. Bring to a simmer and cover, shaking the pan occasionally. When the mussels and clams start popping open, remove them and place in a bowl, about 7 to 9 minutes total. Discard any that do not open. 

Wipe out the pan and heat the olive over medium heat. Add the shallot and garlic and cook until softened, about 2 minutes. Stir in the  Calabrian chile paste and cook for 1 minute more. Add in the tomatoes and cook until they become jammy, pressing down with the back of a wooden spoon, if needed, about 9 to 11 minutes. Season with salt. 

Stir in the shrimp until just cooked through, 1 to 2 minutes. Add the reserved shellfish back to the pan and toss until warmed through. 

Add in the pasta and a bit of pasta water and toss until everything is well combined and the pasta is glossy with sauce, adding more pasta water as needed. 

Transfer to a platter and garnish with the Italian parsley. Serve in bowls.

It’s almost that time…! That’s right, the Feast of the Seven Fishes is nearly upon us. 

I’ve been celebrating since I was born and it is my favorite eating day of the year. 

If you’re not familiar with this blessed day, families celebrate Christmas Eve by having a multi-course, day-long eating extravaganza with, you guessed it, a menu that includes seven fish. 

It is the most fun and trying to get all seven fish in before midnight is always a game of creativity. And, I am always up for the challenge! 

In addition to the pasta dish from my Reel the other day (and the full recipe in my Substack today!) I’ll be serving Dungeness Crab with Aioli, Scallop Crudo and some caviar from @pearlstreetcaviar. Yum!
A very Arthur Avenue wedding anniversary! 14 years, 5 pounds of fresh pasta, 4 pounds of sausage and one very nice table of strangers who let us eat lunch with them. Buon Natale! ❤️🎄🍝

VONGOLE — highly recommend for the Feast of the Seven Fishes! I’ve got a great recipe for it in @nytimes I will link in Stories. 

Also, swipe for my menu from last year 🥹

🍝 Photo by @ryanliebe #feastofthesevenfishes #sevenfishes #christmasevedinner
Merry Christmas from us and this ham. Sending love and peace to all. 🎄🎁💫 🍖

Time for a very brief intermission between Christmas and NYE feasting, so I’m calling for a simple and bright Chicken Piccata for dinner.

I love making bright dishes this time of year. Meyer lemons are in season, so I’ve called for them here, they are sweeter and a bit less acidic than normal lemons and you can eat them rind and all. 

Regular lemons work too if you can’t find Meyer ones. This is the perfect comfort food for this time of year. I’d serve it over rice pilaf or polenta. Enjoy! 

Link for the recipe is in my Stories!

First meal of 2024? Might I suggest @madhungry’s Spatchcoked Chicken with Lemon and Herbs. 

She brilliantly roasts a spatchcoked bird over buttered bread, which toasts in the oven along with the rendered schmaltz. It’s criminally good! 

Serve with a salad of radicchio, fennel, grapefruit and avocado on the side. Perfection 🤌

It’s cold. Let’s make meatballs (and my marinara!)

These ones are turkey meatballs. Ground turkey can be dry, but with the addition of both grated zucchini and mascarpone (both which provide moisture) you end up with light and fluffy meatballs that are quite impressive, if I do say so myself. Link to the full recipe in Stories!
It’s Sunday. It’s a snow day. 🍝 Let’s make Fusilli with Caramelized Onions, Greens, Walnuts and Feta Cheese for dinner!

I’ve been eating a lot of things in bowls lately.

I do my best to use everything in my fridge to create weeknight meals, so as little as possible goes to waste. 

I also look to my busting- at-the-seams pantry to use items that have been in there for some time to try and make some room. 

I said to Chad last night that we could probably live off of what’s in there for over three months without ever leaving the house. And while that’s a somewhat comforting thought, I also found it equally alarming/bordering on hoarder status… 

But, as a result of my thriftiness, I’ve been to able created some pretty great meals such as this one.

Enter… a vegetarian stew for gloomy days. Wild Mushroom and Farro Stew with Greens!
Mi scusa! 🍝🇮🇹
